text:
Anyone been going *deep* with the brand inheritance stuff?
Seemed like a great opportunity to us to take the brand colors, generate full set of shades for each color and then map these to the appropriate semantic color design tokens (through css custom props).

After *a lot* of cursing and messing about with the limited tool that hubl is, we’ve managed to create a css file that generates a list of css custom props per brand color defined in the portal settings.
eg:
```:root {
    --colors-brand-1-900: #580329;
    --colors-brand-1-800: #9d0649;
    --colors-brand-1-700: #e10869;
    --colors-brand-1-600: #f8388e;
…
    --colors-brand-1-100: #fed6e8;
    --colors-brand-1-50: #fff5f9;
    --colors-brand-2-900: #004d1a;
    --colors-brand-2-800: #007627;
…
}```
To me, this feels like a use-case that would be intended? Take some color settings, use them in a css file. It’s even mentioned in the docs:
```In a HTML/HubL or CSS file, you can use the following tokens to access the primary brand color:

{{brand_settings.primaryColor}}
{{brand_settings.colors[0]}}```
Problem though, when adding or changing a brand color, the css file is not regenerated.
I know this is a long shot, but are there any ways/tricks/hacks to get that css file to regenerate when brand settings change?
